<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-720-710  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 720 710.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MacWEEK  August 7 1990 v4 n27 p65(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Coastal Associates Publishing L.P. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Mac falls short in database tasks. (Point/Counterpoint) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Seymour, Jim.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Product:   Apple Macintosh (Microcomputer) (business use).andO;Topic:     Data Base Management SystemsHardware SelectionProcessor SpeedBusiness PlanningMicrocomputers.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Mac falls short in database tasksandM;By Jim SeymourandM;I love the Mac, but it's not a very good database machine.andM;Certainly there are a number of interesting database programs for the Mac.andO;Filevision and Helix showed us what databases could be.andP;  FileMaker redefinedour notion of Everyman's database-management-system program.andP;  DAtabase becameone of the all-time hit desk accessories.andP;  And the current releases of 4thDimension and FoxBASE+/Mac show that graphical-interface database softwaredoesn't have to be slow or limited.andM;But look at almost any vertical-market DBMS application available on the Mac,from medical-office-management programs to video-rental-store packages.andO;They're slow, clumsy, feeble.andP;  Few qualify as good turnkey programs.andM;OK, you say, that's because those developers did a poor job.andP;  But all of them...?andP;  Worse, the Mac is also a poor database-querying machine inmixed-hardware environments.andM;Despite all the hoopla over SQL databases, hardly anyone talks about the mostimportant benefit of standardization on SQL.andP;  It's simple: With shareddatabases running under a SQL program on a server, each of us attached tothat server will be able to use whatever front-end program we wish tocommunicate with that database, as long as those front ends have SQL-querycapabilities.andM;For example, I could use Excel or Lotus 1-2-3 or Paradox on my PC as aSQL-compliant DBMS front end.andP;  In this way, SQL promises PC users freedom towork their own way and to access shared databases -- the core of corporatecomputing -- through their own preferred programs.andM;And the Mac?andP;  Well, SQL-based Mac programs are few and far between.andP;  Andthough Apple talks a lot about CL/1 and connectivity, the fact is that theMac is still a poor relation when querying a mixed-platform networkeddatabase.andM;I haven't even mentioned the spectacular performance of PC databases usingthe multithreading capabilities of OS/2.andP;  Nor that, despite the welcome gainin firepower with the IIfx, Macs still lag behind 80486 PCs in the kind ofabsolute number crunching demanded by databases.andM;Maybe it isn't the Mac's fault but rather that of Mac DBMS programmers andapplication developers.andP;  But in the end, it's the Mac and its users that loseout.andM;Jim Seymour is a consultant on strategic systems and management productivityfor Fortune 500 companies and a columnist for PC Week, PC Magazine andPC/Computing.andO;</TEXT></DOC>